<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longrightarrow )]]></fr:tex> If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a field, then every nonzero ideal contains a unit, which means that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is the only nonzero ideal.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Suppose the only ideals of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is the trivial ideal and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> itself. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> be any nonzero element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(u)=R]]></fr:tex> so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1\in (u)]]></fr:tex>. Hence there must be some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[v\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1=vu]]></fr:tex> (i.e., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-000I.xml"
addr="ra-000I"
title="Unit">unit</fr:link>). Therefore every nonzero element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a unit, hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> must be a field.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
